}

// Semantic direction:
// jsonrpc_message is the union of request, response, and notification.
// jsonrpc_request carries a message_id, method_name, and params_object; expects a response.
// jsonrpc_notification carries method_name and params_object; expects no response.
// jsonrpc_response carries the same message_id as its request, plus result_object or error.
// lsp_transport abstracts the byte-level communication channel.
// stdio_transport reads from stdin and writes to stdout — the standard LSP deployment mode.
// message_framing uses HTTP-style headers: Content-Length gives the byte count of body_bytes.
// header_separator is the blank line (\r\n\r\n) dividing headers from body_bytes.
// read_message reads headers, parses content_length, then reads exactly that many bytes.
// message_loop runs continuously: read_message -> decode_message -> dispatch_message.
// dispatch_message routes to handle_request or handle_notification based on message_id presence.
// handle_request processes the request and sends a jsonrpc_response with the same message_id.
// pending_requests tracks in-flight server-to-client requests awaiting a response.
// cancel_request notifies a handler that the client no longer needs a result.
// progress_token identifies a long-running operation for incremental progress_report updates.
// error_server_not_initialized is returned for any request before the initialize handshake.
// error_content_modified signals that a result was computed on a now-stale document version.

// Primitive flow:
// stdin bytes -> read_message -> content_length + body_bytes
// -> utf8_decode -> json_deserialize -> jsonrpc_message
// -> dispatch_message:
//    request -> handle_request -> result_object or error
//              -> jsonrpc_response -> json_serialize -> encode_message -> write_message -> stdout
//    notification -> handle_notification (no response)
//    cancel -> pending_requests lookup -> cancel handler
// progress: server sends progress_begin notification -> progress_report* -> progress_end

// This defines the JSON-RPC 2.0 transport and message loop
// that forms the communication backbone of the Norscode language server.

